From Sadun Anik Subject Re Win NT what is it In article Scott Reimert writes Somewhere in this thread it has been said that Windows NT tm is a multi user OS as well as multi threading I certainly haven't seen this to be the There are seperate accounts for each person and even seperate directories if that is I don't see an implentation of simultaneuos use Scott It certainly is multi What I have seen from the March Beta is that it doesn't yet come with the stuff which exploits multi user I remember somebody from MS stating that it doesn't allow two users share one My interpretation of this was that one user per console but all the networking and RPC based stuff you I believe ftp and rlogin deamons for NT systems will come from third Somebody already has a Beta version of an unsecure ftpd on the There is no reason why one cannot write a posix based shell like csh on Unix for remote In general I liked NT when I checked it It slow compared to just like any other real OS The beta version although being slow botts up much faster than my SUN Windows subsystems also start up a lot faster than X I believe Bill Gates was right when he stated that NT was not for After playing around with it for a while I was If I owned a busines using a business computer from IBM or some other established vendor I would consider moving to NT platform because it would provide a much cheaper solution If you are running SQL servers It provides the robustness such an application On the other hand if you like your DOS games more or less forget about You can always boot to DOS but in general that defeats the purpose of using Most of NT's features are visible in a networked environment and in such an environment you can't reboot your machine at For personal use I would rather wait for the based Windows release whatever you name it than jump to NT I expect most applications will keep on using until becomes widely Sadun Anik U of Illinois at Urbana Champaign Center for Reliable and High performance Computing e mail